# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-benghazi-attack
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] The **113th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, from January 3, 2013, to January 3, 2015, during the fifth and sixth years of Barack Obama's presidency.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] It was composed of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives based on the results of the 2012 Senate elections and the 2012 House elections.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] The seats in the House were apportioned based on the 2010 United States census.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] It first met in Washington, D.C., on January 3, 2013, and it ended on January 3, 2015.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] Senators elected to regular terms in 2008 were in the last two years of those terms during this Congress.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] The Senate had a Democratic majority, while the House had a Republican majority; such a split would not be repeated until the 118th Congress.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] This was the last time Democrats held control of the Senate until the 117th Congress in 2021.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/113th-congress] [**Section contents:** Senate, House, Joint ] Listed alphabetically by chamber, including Chairperson and Ranking Member.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/13-hours-book] Roman Augustoviz of *Star Tribune* wrote, "'13 Hours' is a jarring narrative at times, but well-flowing.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/13-hours-book] It dwells mostly on the six security operators, who they were, how they prepared for their jobs and how they reacted in a crisis and depended on one another." Glenn C.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/13-hours-book] Altschuler of *The Boston Globe* commented, "Zuckoff focuses on the Benghazi security men...
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/13-hours-book] In 2016, the book was adapted into a major feature film directed by Michael Bay and starring James Badge Dale, John Krasinski, and Max Martini.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/13-hours-book] The film received mixed reviews based on its perceived political stance, but nevertheless grossed a total of $69.4 million worldwide against a production budget of $50 million.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The **14.5×114 mm** (.57 calibre) is a heavy machine gun and anti-materiel rifle cartridge used by the Soviet Union, the former Warsaw Pact, modern Russia, and other countries.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The 14.5 × 114 mm has 42.53 ml (655 grains H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The exterior shape of the case was designed to promote reliable case feeding and extraction in bolt-action rifles, semi-automatic rifles, and heavy machine guns alike, under extreme conditions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] 14.5 × 114 mm maximum cartridge dimensions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] All dimensions in millimetres (mm), but angles may be measured in degrees or degrees-arcminutes-arcseconds (° ′ ″); alpha is 22.5°.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] Americans define the shoulder angle at alpha/2 = 22.25°.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The most common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 1 in 455 mm (17.91 in), with 8 grooves, land ⌀ 14.50 mm (0.571 in), and groove ⌀ 14.95 mm (0.589 in).
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] Assuming a muzzle velocity of 1 km/s (0.62 mi/s), as is roughly typical for it, this gives it a muzzle angular frequency of ≈ 131868 rpm (13809 rad/s; 2.198 kHz).
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] According to the official guidelines, the 14.5 × 114 mm case can handle up to 360 MPa (52,213 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] In C.I.P. regulated countries every rifle cartridge combo has to be proofed at 125% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to be certified for sale to consumers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] Cartridges use lacquered steel cases and percussion primers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] Some countries also use brass cartridge cases.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The propellant consists of 28.8 g (1.02 oz) smokeless powder with seven tubes, designated as "5/7NA powder".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] Two different versions of bullet series are known, the earlier has a conventional bullet jacket with a boat-tail.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] These have a long engraving portion that causes considerable barrel wear.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The newer bullet types have a smaller engraving portion with a rounder boat-tail and were used from about 1957 onward.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] The cartridge has been manufactured in Bulgaria, China, Egypt, Hungary, Iraq, North Korea, Poland, Romania, Russia, and the former Czechoslovakia.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] In addition to being chambered in multiple calibers, the Ukrainian Horizon's Lord rifle uses its own proprietary "12.7 × 114 HL" cartridge made by necking down a 14.5 × 114 mm cartridge case to accept a .50 BMG bullet.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/14-5-114mm] In essence, the 14.5 × 114mm cartridge is the parent case for the 12.7 × 114 HL.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/1979-u-s-embassy-burning-in-libya] Embassy in Tripoli, Libya, was burned during protests over allegations that the United States was involved in the Grand Mosque seizure in Mecca, Saudi Arabia.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/1979-u-s-embassy-burning-in-libya] The United States had already withdrawn the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/1979-u-s-embassy-burning-in-libya] Following the 1979 attack, all remaining U.S. government personnel were withdrawn and the embassy closed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/1979-u-s-embassy-burning-in-libya] Diplomatic presence resumed on February 8, 2004, with the arrival of the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/1979-u-s-embassy-burning-in-libya] That mission was upgraded to a Liaison Office on June 24, 2004.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] The **2000 United States House of Representatives election for the 1st district in Illinois** took place on November 7, 2000, to elect a representative from Illinois's 1st congressional district for the 107th United States Congress.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Incumbent Democratic representative Bobby Rush faced a primary challenge from Illinois Senator and future President Barack Obama.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush defeated Obama 61 percent to 30 percent, with other candidates combining for the remaining nine percent.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush later defeated his Republican opponent, Raymond Wardingley, 88 percent to 12 percent, ensuring his reelection.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Subsequent to this election, Obama was elected to the Senate in 2004, and later elected President in 2008.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Illinois's 1st congressional district is a minority-majority district.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] At the time of the election, 65 percent of its constituents were African American.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] In redistricting after the 1990 United States census, the district was extended into the suburbs for the first time in 90 years, but a majority of the districts' residents (70%) lived in Chicago.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] A strongly Democratic district, only twice since 1966 has a Republican candidate for United States Congress received over 20% of the vote.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush was involved in the civil rights movement of the 1960s.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] He was a member of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) and a former member and founder of the Illinois chapter of the Black Panther Party.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] After coordinating a medical clinic that treated sickle cell anemia, Rush served as an alderman and was first elected to represent Illinois's 1st district in 1992.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush ran for Mayor of Chicago against Richard M.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Daley in 1999 and lost, receiving only 28% of the vote, making him appear electorally vulnerable.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama, at age 38, was a lecturer at the University of Chicago and a two-term state Senator.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Also challenging Rush were Donne Trotter, a state senator, and George Roby, a police officer.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Raymond Wardingley, a perennial candidate who worked as a clown, ran unopposed for the Republican nomination.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Early polling showed Rush's name recognition started off at 90 percent, with Obama's at 11 percent.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush had 70 percent approval, while Obama had 8 percent approval.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] In the head-to-head matchup, forty-seven percent of the people polled favored Rush, 10 percent favored Obama, and 5 percent supported Trotter, who is also African American.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Most of Obama's support came from White Americans.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] In mid-October, Rush's son, Huey, was murdered, leading Obama to put his campaign on hold.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Governor George Ryan called the Illinois Legislature to a special session to re-enact a package of gun control bills, a pet issue of Rush, which had been overturned by the Illinois Supreme Court.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama supported the package, but the session dragged on towards Christmas.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama annually spent the Christmas vacation in Hawaii with his family visiting his grandmother, who raised him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama left Illinois, expecting the session would continue into January.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] However, a crucial vote took place earlier than expected, failing by five votes with Obama and others absent.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama came under fire for missing the vote though he said he would have flown back sooner, but his 18-month-old daughter was sick.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Meanwhile, Rush received an outpouring of sympathy that aided his campaign.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] As Obama lived in Hyde Park, a more affluent neighborhood with a higher percentage of White voters than the rest of the district, the narrative of the race became "the Black Panther against the professor." Obama frequently came off as uptight.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Rush criticized Obama: "Barack Obama went to Harvard and became an educated fool.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] We’re not impressed with these folks with these Eastern elite degrees.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Then–State Representative Tom Dart supported Obama and organized on his behalf in the 19th ward.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama raised enough money to remain competitive with Rush.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] However, he neither connected with the working-class African Americans of the district nor provided a convincing reason for them to vote against Rush.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama later wrote: "Less than halfway into the campaign, I knew in my bones that I was going to lose.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Wardingley ran for the Republican nomination without opposition.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama later said about his loss to Rush "I got my rear end handed to me" and acknowledged his own hubris.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] However, many analysts believe that Obama's loss helped him to learn from his mistakes, which enabled him to run more successful campaigns in 2004 and 2008.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Obama was seen as a stiff policy wonk, and he used the experience to hone his ability to connect with voters.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Also, Obama increased his focus on the Illinois Senate, improving his legislative accomplishments.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] In 2004, Obama was the keynote speaker at the Democratic National Convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] After his speech, political pundits speculated about his future as a possible presidential candidate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] He then defeated John McCain, also a senator, in the general election to become President of the United States.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-illinois-s-1st-congressional-district-election] Bobby Rush served a total of thirty years in the House of Representatives, retiring in early 2023 after 15 terms.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In the United States Senate election held in the State of New York on November 7, 2000, Hillary Rodham Clinton, then first lady of the United States and the first presidential spouse to run for political office, defeated U.S. representative Rick Lazio.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The general election coincided with the U.S. presidential election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The race began in November 1998 when four-term incumbent senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan announced his retirement, making this the first open Senate seat since the 1958 Senate election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Both the Democratic Party and Republican Party sought high-profile candidates to compete for the open seat.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By early 1999, Clinton and New York City mayor Rudy Giuliani were the frontrunners for their parties' respective nominations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton and her husband, President Bill Clinton, purchased a house in Chappaqua, New York, in September 1999; she thereby became eligible for the election, although she faced accusations of carpetbagging since she had never resided in the state before.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The lead in statewide polls swung from Clinton to Giuliani and back to Clinton as the campaigns featured both successful strategies and mistakes as well as dealing with current events.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In late April and May 2000, Giuliani's medical, romantic, marital, and political lives all collided in a tumultuous four-week period, culminating in his withdrawal from the race on May 19.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Republicans chose lesser-known U.S. representative Rick Lazio to replace him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The election included a record $90 million in campaign expenditures between Clinton, Lazio, and Giuliani and national visibility.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton showed strength in normally Republican upstate areas and a debate blunder by Lazio solidified Clinton's previously shaky support among women.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton won the election in November 2000 with 55 percent of the vote to Lazio's 43 percent, and became the first woman elected to the Senate from New York.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] When four-term senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan announced his retirement in November 1998, his previously safe U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Senate seat became open in the 2000 U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Both parties tried to find high-profile candidates to run for it.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] New York City mayor Rudy Giuliani, who was prevented by term limits from running for mayoral reelection in 2001, immediately indicated interest.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Due to his high profile and visibility, Giuliani was supported by the New York State Republican Party, even though he had irritated many by endorsing incumbent Democratic governor Mario Cuomo over Republican George Pataki in 1994.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani became the presumptive Republican nominee, and by April 1999 had formed a formal exploratory committee for a Senate run.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] There were still possible Republican primary opponents.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Rick Lazio, a U.S. representative representing Suffolk County on Long Island, was raising money and had a candidacy announcement scheduled for August 16; he had openly discussed a primary against Giuliani, believing his more conservative record would be appealing to Republican primary voters.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In early August, under pressure from state and national Republican figures, Pataki endorsed Giuliani.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Pataki prevailed upon Lazio to forgo his candidacy, which Lazio agreed to despite frustration that Giuliani had still not officially announced that he was running; Lazio said, "If the mayor wants to be a candidate, I think he needs to get into this race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] It is time to put the soap opera aside and step up to the plate." Nassau County U.S. representative Peter T.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] King also considered running and had raised some funds.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] U.S. representative Nita Lowey was the candidate first expected to be the Democratic nominee, while other mentioned possible candidates included secretary of housing and urban development Andrew Cuomo, state comptroller Carl McCall, as well as U.S. representative Carolyn Maloney.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] State Democratic figures were concerned that neither Lowey nor the others had the star power to rival Giuliani, and that the seat would be lost.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Late in 1998, prominent Democratic politicians and advisors, including U.S. representative Charles Rangel, urged First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton to run for the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] An unprecedented action if she did it, Clinton spent considerable time mulling over the idea while Lowey waited in the wings.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Her political advisors told her the race would be difficult and some of them told her she would lose.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] She waited for the impeachment proceedings of Bill Clinton to conclude, which they did with his acquittal on February 12, 1999.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On February 16, 1999, the First Lady's office announced that she was considering running for the Senate seat.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Once it was clear Clinton was going to run, Lowey stepped aside, although she would be disappointed at the lost opportunity.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On July 7, 1999, Clinton formally announced an exploratory committee for the Senate run; the setting was Moynihan's farm in Pindars Corners, in rural Delaware County.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Bill Clinton was less than enthusiastic about her candidacy.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The staging of the event was brokered by the Clintons' political consultant Mandy Grunwald.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Hillary Clinton embarked upon a "listening tour" of all parts of New York after her entrance into the race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] She planned to visit all 62 counties in New York, talking to New Yorkers in small-group settings according to the principles of retail politics.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] During the race, she spent considerable time campaigning in traditionally Republican upstate regions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton faced charges of carpetbagging, since she had never resided in the State of New York nor directly participated in state politics prior to her Senate race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Meanwhile, in September 1999, the Clintons purchased a $1.7 million, 11-room, Dutch Colonial style home in Chappaqua, New York, north of New York City.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Even the commonplace activity of house hunting leading up to this was the subject of considerable media attention; coverage of personal lives would be the norm in this contest of two "electrifying and polarizing figures" (as one reporter put it).
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In November 1999, Hillary Clinton announced that she would set aside most of her official duties as First Lady in order to take up residency in New York and pursue her campaign.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Her move-in took place in January 2000, with the house furnished with many of the couple's possessions from their Arkansas days.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] It became the first time since Woodrow Wilson's first wife died in 1914 that a president lived in the White House without a spouse.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The early stages of her campaign were not without mistakes, and as she later wrote, "Mistakes in New York politics aren't easily brushed aside." In a much-publicized move, Clinton donned a New York Yankees baseball cap at a June 1999 event when she had been a lifelong fan of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] This brought her much criticism, and Thomas Kuiper would later write an anti-Clinton book titled: *I've Always Been a Yankees Fan: Hillary Clinton in Her Own Words*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton said she had to develop an American League rooting interest, since fans of the Cubs were not expected to root for the American League Chicago White Sox.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In her 2003 autobiography, she said that putting on the hat had been a "bad move", but reiterated what had been reported in the press prior to the incident, that she had been "a die-hard Mickey Mantle fan;" the book included a photograph of her with a Yankees cap on from 1992.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Some Israeli supporters said that Clinton never should have kissed the wife of the Palestinian leader, especially after such inflammatory remarks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The following day, Clinton denounced Suha Arafat's allegations, and said that Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat had told her Suha Arafat had been referring to 'tear gas' and not 'poison gas'.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The kiss became a campaign issue, especially with Jewish voters.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton said it was a formality akin to a handshake, saying that to not have done so would have caused a diplomatic incident.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton faced an erosion of support from women voters during her campaign, with her numbers declining throughout 1999.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] This was partly a typical pattern seen with women candidates where they have an early surge of female support, which then wears off, and it was partly due to her early campaign stumbles.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] But it also reflected the particular set of mixed feelings that women had towards Clinton's marriage and the ambition and the power she derived from it.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The problem was especially acute among some female demographics; one of her longtime advisers later said, "Women in the educated professional class?
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Her political positions were well matched to the different constituencies in the state that she targeted.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In a January 2000 appearance on the *Late Show with David Letterman*, she established a rapport with the host that would continue throughout her Senate years and into her 2008 presidential campaign.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton formally announced her official candidacy in Purchase, New York in February 2000, adopting the simple name "Hillary" for her campaign literature.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Distrustful of the press since her husband's 1992 presidential campaign and her early days as First Lady, she imposed limits on her availability to the press van following her.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Associated Press reporter Beth Harpaz later recounted a typical day from this time: "But we'd been told there'd be no 'avail' today, and we'd accepted it.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] That didn't prevent me from feeling slightly humiliated.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] An early January 1999 Marist Institute of Public Opinion poll showed Giuliani trailing Clinton by 10 points.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By January 2000, the Marist poll showed Giuliani up by 9 points.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani's tactics involved intentionally baiting the Clinton campaign with deliberate overstatements, keeping them off balance and behind in the response cycle.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani emphasized his depiction of Clinton as a carpetbagger.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] He made a one-day visit to Little Rock, Arkansas, where he announced he would fly the Arkansas state flag over New York's City Hall.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] When Hillary Clinton visited New York from Washington, he said, "I hope she knows the way.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] I hope she doesn't get lost on one of the side streets." Giuliani's campaign prepared a 315-page opposition research dossier that went back to her time at Wellesley College; it included eleven pages of what they termed "Stupid Actions and Remarks".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Giuliani campaign had no problems raising money, getting over 40 percent of its funds from out-of-state and outraising Clinton overall two-to-one.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Giuliani campaign showed some structural weaknesses.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] So closely identified with New York City, he had somewhat limited appeal to naturally Republican voters in Upstate New York.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Farmersville Garbage Scandal was indicative of his lower levels of support upstate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By late December 1999, Clinton adapted to Giuliani's psychological warfare, saying in response to one such gambit, "I can't be responding every time the mayor gets angry.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Because that's all I would do." A February 2000 attempt by Giuliani to capitalize on a Clinton campaign event's accidental playing of Billy Joel's suburban drug tale "Captain Jack" led to more ridicule for him than for her.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani was on stage in male disco garb spoofing John Travolta in *Saturday Night Fever*, but also appeared in drag in taped video clips that reworked the "Rudy/Rudia" theme of a past Inner Circle dinner, as well as in an exchange with Joan Rivers that sought to make fun of Clinton.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Other performers' skits made fun of Clinton's Yankees claim and the infidelity of her husband.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The New York Police Department's fatal shooting of Patrick Dorismond on March 15, 2000, inflamed Giuliani's already strained relations with the city's minority communities, and Clinton seized on it as a major campaign issue.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By April, reports showed Clinton gaining upstate and generally outworking Giuliani, who stated that his duties as mayor prevented him from campaigning more.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] He gave priority to city duties over campaign activities.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By this time, Clinton was 8 to 10 points ahead of Giuliani in the polls.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani's marriage to his wife, broadcast journalist and actress Donna Hanover, had been distant since 1996, and the two were rarely seen in public together.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] There had been no formal announcement of any change in their relationship, although Hanover had indicated that she and their children would not move to Washington if Giuliani won the race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Beginning in October 1999, a new woman was being spotted at mayoral functions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By March 2000, Giuliani had stopped wearing his wedding ring and was being seen more in the company of this other woman, including at the Inner Circle press dinner, the St.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Patrick's Day parade, and town hall meetings, but it was not yet fully clear whether the relationship was personal or professional.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] While this woman had become a frequent subject of insider talk among the New York political circle, she had not been mentioned in the press.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On April 20 Hanover announced that she would soon be taking over the lead role in Eve Ensler's controversial play *The Vagina Monologues*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Political observers speculated that Hanover was partly engaging in a political act against her husband, as Ensler was a friend and supporter of Hillary Clinton and the role would not go over well with social conservatives within the Republican Party.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani declined to say whether he would attend one of her performances.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On April 22, the *New York Post* obtained photographs of Giuliani openly strolling on a Manhattan street with the other woman after they left a restaurant, but did not have more than a first name for her; the *Post* sat on the story, but it was clear the relationship was a personal one.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On April 26, television channel NY1 reported that Giuliani had undergone a second round of tests for prostate cancer at Mount Sinai Medical Center; the same disease had led to the death of his father.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On April 28, Giuliani held a news conference to announce that he did in fact have prostate cancer, but it was in an early stage.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] He was unsure of which of several types of treatment he might undergo, and that decision would impact whether he could stay in the Senate race or not.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Hanover was not present at the conference, but issued a note saying she would support him in his decision process.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] As Giuliani mulled over his medical options, on May 1 Hanover announced that she was postponing her appearance in *The Vagina Monologues* due to "personal family circumstances." On May 2 the *New York Daily News* published a brief item about Giuliani's other woman, without name or description.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On May 3 the *New York Post* finally published its photographs of Giuliani and the woman, now identified as Judith Nathan, leaving a restaurant together, under the front-page headline "Rudy's Mystery Brunch Pal is Upper East Side Divorcée".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The next days were filled with New York media coverage on Nathan's background and on the relationship.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On May 6 Hanover held an unusually-located news conference at the back of St.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On May 10, Giuliani held what *The New York Times* described as an "extraordinary, emotional news conference" in Bryant Park to announce that he was seeking a separation from Hanover, saying, "This is very, very painful.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] For quite some time it's probably been apparent that Donna and I lead in many ways independent and separate lives." Regarding Nathan, Giuliani said "I'm going to need her now more than maybe I did before", making reference to his battle with cancer and her background in nursing.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Regarding the Senate race, he again did not commit to a decision, saying, "I don't really care about politics right now.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] I'm thinking about my family, the people that I love and what can be done that's honest and truthful and that protects them the best.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Politics comes at least second, maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] It'll all work itself out some way politically." Giuliani had, however, neglected to inform Hanover in advance of his announcement; her reaction was described as distraught.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Three hours later, she held her own news conference at Gracie Mansion, where she said, "Today's turn of events brings me great sadness.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] I had hoped to keep this marriage together.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Hanover continued, "Beginning last May, I made a major effort to bring us back together.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Rudy and I re-established some of our personal intimacy through the fall.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] State Republican leaders, who until now had avoided talk of replacements for Giuliani should he not run, now gave more attention to the matter, with the state party convention coming up on May 30.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Former possible contenders Rick Lazio and Pete King immediately indicated they were available; other names mentioned included Wall Street financier Theodore J.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Forstmann and Governor Pataki, although the latter indicated no interest.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani continued to ponder his Senate race decision; when he had dinner with Nathan on May 12, they were trailed by a flock of photographers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani canceled campaigning and fundraising trips to upstate New York and California on May 13, suggesting he would not run, but then resumed fundraising and suggested he was inclined towards running on May 15.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Two Republican county chairmen became upset at the indecision, saying, "Like *Waiting for Godot*, we have *Waiting for Rudy*", and, "We need a decision.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Because this is getting ridiculous." A top state Republican said, "He seem[s] to like the attention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] He seems to be going through some sort of catharsis in public.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] And we're like psychiatrists watching it.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Finally, on May 19, Giuliani held what *The New York Times* again described as "an emotional, riveting news conference" that "reached a new level of introspection" to announce that he was dropping out of the Senate race: "This is not the right time for me to run for office.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] If it were six months ago or it were a year from now or the timing were a little different, maybe it would be different.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] But it isn't different and that's the way life is." He added that, "I used to think the core of me was in politics, probably.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] When you feel your mortality and your humanity you realize that, that the core of you is first of all being able to take care of your health." He said that he would instead devote the remainder of his mayoralty trying to overcome the hostile relations he had with many of the city's minority groups.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In particular, Governor Pataki — who never cared much for Giuliani to begin with — was strongly in favor of Lazio, and praised him as a "fresh, unencumbered challenger" to Clinton.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio accepted the unanimous approval of delegates to the Republican Party state convention at a hotel ballroom in Buffalo on May 30.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton now faced a lesser-known candidate in Lazio.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] While a relative moderate among House Republicans, Lazio had frequently supported former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, a largely despised figure among many New Yorkers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio did bring to the table a suburban background familiar to many New Yorkers, and had a reputation as an energetic campaigner.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] One formality left were New York's late-in-the-season primary elections on September 12, which in this case merely served to ratify the state party conventions' choices.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] I stood there for a minute, staring at my name." In any case, the general election was already well underway.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The contest drew considerable national attention and both candidates were well-funded.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By the end of the race, Democrat Clinton and Republicans Lazio and Giuliani had spent a combined $90 million, the most of any U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio outspent Clinton $40 million to $29 million, with Clinton also getting several million dollars in soft money from Democratic organizations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton also brought in Terry McAuliffe and Laura Hartigan, political veterans from her husband's presidential campaigns, to assist with her fundraising efforts.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Among Clinton antagonists circles, direct mail-based fundraising groups such as the Emergency Committee to Stop Hillary Rodham Clinton sprung up, sending out solicitations regarding the "carpetbagging" issue.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton secured a broad base of support, including endorsements from conservation groups and organized labor, but notably not the New York City police union which endorsed Lazio while firefighters supported Clinton.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] While Clinton had a solid base of support in New York City, candidates and observers expected the race to be decided in upstate New York where 45 percent of the state's voters lived.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] During the campaign, Clinton vowed to improve the economic picture in upstate New York, promising that her plan would deliver 200,000 New York jobs over six years.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Her plan included specific tax credits with the purpose of rewarding job creation and encouraging business investment, especially in the high-tech sector.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] She called for targeted personal tax cuts for college tuition and long-term care.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio faced a unique tactical problem campaigning upstate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The major issue there was the persistently weak local economy, which Lazio hoped to link to his opponent's husband's tenure in office.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Attacks on the state of the upstate economy were frequently interpreted as criticism of incumbent Republican governor George Pataki, however, limiting the effect of this line of attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In July 2000, the release of *State of a Union: Inside the Complex Marriage of Bill and Hillary Clinton* by author Jerry Oppenheimer led to reports that Clinton had called someone a "fucking Jew bastard" in 1974.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The report, which received international media coverage, "rocked" Clinton's campaign, with *The Daily Telegraph* describing the campaign as having "mounted a frantic damage limitation exercise after details of the alleged incident were leaked".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton had reportedly screamed the insult at Paul Fray, who managed Bill Clinton's unsuccessful 1974 congressional campaign.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Bill Clinton did allow that Hillary might have simply called Fray a "bastard".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Opponents continued to make the carpetbagging issue a focal point throughout the race and during debates.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Talk radio hammered on this, with New York-based Sean Hannity issuing a daily mantra, "Name me three things Hillary Clinton has ever done for the people of New York!" Clinton's supporters pointed out that the state was receptive to national leaders, such as Robert F.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Kennedy who was elected to the Senate in 1964 despite similar accusations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In the end, according to exit polls conducted in the race, a majority of the voters dismissed the carpetbagging issue as unimportant.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] During the campaign, Independent Counsel Robert Ray filed his final reports regarding the long-running Whitewater, "Travelgate", and "Filegate" investigations of the White House, each of which included specific investigations of Hillary Clinton actions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The reports exonerated her on the files matter, said there was insufficient evidence regarding her role in Whitewater, and said that she had made factually false statements regarding the Travel Office firings but there was insufficient evidence to prosecute her.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Although *The New York Times* editorialized that the release of the reports seemed possibly timed to coincide with the Senate election, in practice the findings were not seen as likely to sway many voters' opinions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] A September 13, 2000 debate between Lazio and Clinton proved important.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio was on the warpath against soft money and the amounts of it coming from the Democratic National Committee into Clinton's campaign, and challenged Clinton to agree to ban soft money from both campaigns.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] He left his podium and waved his proposed paper agreement in Clinton's face; many debate viewers thought he had invaded her personal space and as a result Clinton's support among women voters solidified.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Late in the campaign, Lazio criticized Clinton for accepting campaign donations from various Arab groups in the wake of the USS *Cole* bombing.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Lazio campaign orchestrated a wave of telephone calls to voters using this attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] This issue caused former New York Mayor Ed Koch to take out ads telling Lazio to "stop with the sleaze already," and did not change the dynamic of the race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Some of Lazio's campaign strategists would later say that the *Cole*-based attack had backfired and became the campaign's biggest blunder.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] New Square had voted almost unanimously for Clinton in the New York Senate race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] A lawyer following the matter stated that even if Clinton had promised to lobby her husband for clemency in exchange for the town's votes — a claim for which there was no proof — it would be difficult to establish a crime had taken place: "Politicians make promises all the time.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] That's nothing new — or illegal." Clinton acknowledged sitting in on a post-election meeting discussing possible clemency for the four, but said she had played no part in her husband's decision.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] A federal investigation launched to investigate various Clinton pardons, closed its investigation of the New Square matter in June 2002 by taking no action against Bill, Hillary Clinton, or any residents of New Square.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Hillary Clinton's former finance director, David Rosen, was indicted on January 7, 2005, on campaign finance charges related to a fund-raising event produced by Peter F.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The Justice Department indictment charged Rosen with filing false reports with the Federal Election Commission by reporting only $400,000 in contributions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On May 27, 2005, the jury acquitted Rosen on all counts.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On January 5, 2006, it was reported that Clinton's campaign group agreed to pay a $35,000 fine related to the underreporting of the fundraiser's expenses.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Peter Paul also filed a civil suit in this matter, *Paul v.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] On April 10, 2006, the judge in charge of the case removed Hillary Clinton as a defendant, citing a lack of evidence, but leaving open the possibility that she might still be called to testify as a witness in the case.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The removal was upheld by the California Second District Court of Appeal on October 16, 2007.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton won the election on November 7 with 55 percent of the vote to Lazio's 43 percent, a difference larger than most observers had expected.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton won the traditionally Democratic base of New York City by large margins, and carried suburban Westchester County, but lost heavily populated Long Island, part of which Lazio represented in Congress.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] She won 13 of 61 counties, with surprising victories in Upstate counties, such as Cayuga, Rensselaer, and Niagara.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Overall, she lost Upstate to Lazio by only 3 percentage points, to which her win has been attributed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The victory of a Democrat in the Senate election was not assured, because in recent decades the Republicans had won about half the elections for governor and senator.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio's bid was handicapped by the weak performance of George W.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Bush in New York in the 2000 election, but it was also clear Hillary Clinton had made substantial inroads in upstate New York prior to Lazio's entry into the race.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Exit polls also showed a large gender gap with Clinton running stronger than expected among moderate women and unaffiliated women.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton's victory would establish her as an effective campaigner and an electoral force on her own, able to capture Republican and independent votes and overcome her polarizing image.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] She would easily win re-election in 2006, and in 2007 began her presidential campaign for 2008.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Lazio gave up his House seat to run for Senate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Following his defeat, which set a record for the most money spent in a losing Senate effort, he took positions in the corporate world and avoided electoral politics until becoming a candidate in New York's 2010 gubernatorial election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] However, he was defeated by a wide margin in the Republican primary.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani would undergo treatment for his cancer and eventually recover; he would also divorce Donna Hanover and eventually marry Judith Nathan.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] After his campaign withdrawal, his political future looked uncertain at best.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] But less than a year after the senate general election, the September 11 attacks took place, with Giuliani still mayor.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani's performance in the aftermath of September 11 earned him many accolades and resurrected his political prospects.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] After a successful stint in the private sector, in 2007 he also began his presidential campaign for 2008.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Throughout much of 2007, Clinton and Giuliani led in national polls for their parties' respective nominations, and media reports often looked back to the 2000 "race that wasn't" as a preview of what might lie in wait for the entire nation in 2008.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Such extrapolating ended with the Giuliani campaign's precipitous decline and January 2008 withdrawal.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton as well failed to gain the 2008 nomination and, in June 2008, she finished in a close second place to Illinois Senator Barack Obama.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In December 2008, Lowey would have another chance at the Senate seat, when Clinton was nominated for U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Secretary of State by President-elect Obama and Lowey was considered a front-runner to be named as her appointed replacement.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] But Lowey withdrew from consideration, as in the intervening years she had gained enough seniority to become one of the powerful "cardinals" on the House Appropriations Committee and did not want to relinquish that position.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] When Caroline Kennedy announced her interest in the vacancy, comparisons were drawn to Clinton in 2000, with both being famous people seeking to hold elective office for the first time.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Others pointed out that Clinton had won election to the office while Kennedy would first be appointed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In any case, Kennedy's effort soon faltered, in part due to not having the same desire or willingness to work for the seat as Clinton had had, and she soon withdrew as abruptly as she had entered.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Kirsten Gillibrand received the appointment, and attention then turned to who would run against her in the 2010 Senate special election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] By November 2009, Giuliani was seriously considering a run for his old would-have-been Senate seat, but the following month he announced he was not running for it or anything else in 2010, signalling an end to his political career.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Republicans ended up nominating former congressman Joe DioGuardi, whom Gillibrand beat easily.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani and Clinton got another chance to battle each other during the 2016 U.S. presidential election, when she was the Democratic nominee and he was one of the few high-profile Republicans to enthusiastically campaign for that party's nominee, Donald Trump.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] A Clinton spokesperson responded by pointing out that it was Giuliani who had left the 2000 senatorial race in part for health reasons, not Clinton.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani said Clinton was "too stupid to be president" for having stayed married to her husband following the Lewinsky scandal.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Clinton sent some mild barbs Giuliani's way during the Alfred E.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Smith Memorial Foundation Dinner in October 2016, to which Giuliani responded to with stone-faced silence rather than the usual playing-along mirth.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The former mayor also issued a false charge against Clinton's statements regarding her role following the September 11 attacks that he had to apologize for.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] And in the days leading up to the election, Giuliani implied, and then denied, that he had had inside knowledge of the FBI's late-in-the-campaign reopening of its investigation into the Clinton emails matter.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] In the event, he was not selected for either position.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] The attacks continued; in March 2018 Giuliani made a joke at a fundraiser at Trump's Mar-a-Lago resort, the premise of which was that Clinton was almost too fat to fit through doorways.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Judith Giuliani was reported to have given her husband a "most foul look" following the remark; the Giulianis announced they were getting divorced a few weeks later.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] News of the breakup caused media outlets to recall how the Rudy-Judith relationship had all first come to light during the hectic weeks of the 2000 senatorial campaign.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Giuliani became even more in the public spotlight as a central figure in the Trump–Ukraine scandal and the attempts to overturn the 2020 United States presidential election, and then as the subject of a federal investigation about possible wrongdoing regarding his actions in Ukraine.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2000-united-states-senate-election-in-new-york] Asked about her onetime campaign opponent in April 2021, Clinton said that Giuliani has "been behaving so erratically and seemingly illegally for so long" that "I don't recognize him now.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The 2004 Democratic National Convention was famous for the keynote speech of Barack Obama, who would go on to be elected President four years later.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] New Mexico Governor Bill Richardson served as chairman of the convention, while former presidential advisor to Bill Clinton, Lottie Shackelford, served as vice chairwoman of the convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The 2004 Democratic National Convention marked the formal end of the active primary election season, although all meaningful primary elections had finished months earlier.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] After the convention, John Kerry and John Edwards were defeated by the incumbent George W.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Bush and Dick Cheney in the general election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The 2004 Democratic National Convention featured a theme for each day of the convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The first night of the meeting focused on the theme "Plan for America's Future" with speeches devoted to building optimism for John Kerry's candidacy.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The second night of the meeting focused on the theme "A Lifetime of Strength and Service" devoted to John Kerry's biography and his path to his nomination.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The third night of the meeting focused on the theme "A Stronger More Secure America" devoted to issues of homeland security and the global war on terror.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The last night of the meeting focused on the theme "Stronger at Home, Respected in the World" devoted to the overall agenda of the party to secure the borders, improving domestic welfare while at the same time promoting international cooperation in world affairs.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The phrase "Help is on the Way" was often repeated by speakers such as John Edwards.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] This was the first major party presidential nominating convention to be held since the terrorist attacks of September 11 attacks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] During the convention, there was a memorial service to honor the victims of the attacks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Haleema Salie, who lost her daughter, son-in-law, and unborn grandchild on American Flight 11, spoke.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The 2004 Democratic National Convention successfully passed an official party platform.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] A forty-three page document, the party platform was entitled "Strong at Home, Respected in the World" – also the name of the theme conveyed on the last night of the convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The first part of the platform was called "A Strong, Respected America".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The section defined specific goals and actions to defeat terrorism, to keep weapons of mass destruction from the hands of terrorists, to promote world peace and security, to strengthen the military, to achieve energy independence and to strengthen homeland security.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The second part of the platform was called, "A Strong, Growing Economy".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The final part of the platform was called, "A Strong American Community." It stressed the diversity of the nation and the importance of upholding civil rights as a major tenet of the party.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] After an initial notice to 34 cities, 10 cities requested the RFP to host the convention: Atlanta, Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Detroit, Houston, Miami, New York City and Pittsburgh.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Of those, Baltimore, Boston, Detroit, Miami and New York City submitted bids.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Baltimore's bid was considered a long-shot.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Boston, Detroit, Miami and New York City were selected as the finalist cities.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Each of the finalist cities received visits from members of the Democratic National Committee during the site selection process.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Boston was announced as the host of the convention on November 13, 2002.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The 2004 Democratic National Convention was the first major party presidential nominating convention to held in Boston.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] With John Kerry arising as the winner of the primaries, it ultimately was one of the few presidential nominating conventions that was held in the home state of the party's nominee.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] As a result of the selection of Boston, organizers of the Reebok Pro Summer League developmental basketball program had to fold the league into the upstart Las Vegas Summer League due to a lack of lodging in the Boston area.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Until Chicago, Illinois, was selected as the host of the 2024 Democratic National Convention, 2004 was the last time that either major party chose to hold their convention in a state that was not considered to be a swing state (the Republicans held their 2004 convention in New York City).
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Coast Guard, and other governmental organizations took many security measures to protect the participants of the Democratic National Convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Security measures included bomb-sniffing dogs, 7-feet high metal barricades, a ban on corporate and private flights at Logan International Airport, along with the temporary closure of Interstate 93.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Other Bostonians took advantage of the meeting as a national stage for specific agendas.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The police union, for example, gained attention with threats of picketing of delegates from entering and exiting functions – a dilemma for Democrats as the party has traditionally been an ally of organized labor.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Having worked without a contract for two years, the Boston Police Patrolmen's Association struck a deal with Boston mayor Thomas Menino for a new contract, avoiding a major embarrassment for the party.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] State Senator Barack Obama, the Illinois Democratic candidate for United States Senate, delivered the convention's keynote address on Tuesday, July 27, 2004.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] His unexpected landslide victory in the March 2004 Illinois U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Senate Democratic primary had made him overnight a rising star within the national Democratic Party, started speculation about a presidential future, and led to the reissue of his memoir, *Dreams from My Father*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] His keynote address, although not carried by the commercial broadcast television networks, was well received, which further elevated his status within the Democratic Party and led to his reissued memoir becoming a bestseller.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] As the keynote speaker, Obama set the tone for the party platform.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] We coach Little League in the blue states, and yes, we've got some gay friends in the red states.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] There are patriots who opposed the war in Iraq, and there are patriots who supported the war in Iraq.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Obama noted his interracial and international heritage: he was born in Honolulu, Hawaii to a Kenyan immigrant father and a white mother from Kansas.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] "In no other country on Earth is my story even possible", Obama proclaimed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Following the speech political commentator Chris Matthews rightly predicted "I just saw the first black president".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Not yet formally nominated for the vice presidency, John Edwards took the stage at the convention to give the first major national speech of his political career.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Delegates raised red-and-white vertical "Edwards" banners and chanted his name.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The theme of Edwards's address was the divide between the "two Americas", his populist message throughout the primary campaign and now one embraced by Kerry.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] He tied the division to his own roots in North Carolina, and introduced his family to the audience.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Edwards addressed his parents from the podium: "You taught me the values that I carry in my heart: faith, family, responsibility, opportunity for everyone.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] You taught me that there's dignity and honor in a hard day's work.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] And we're going to close corporate loopholes.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] We're going to cut government contractors and wasteful spending.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Many pundits noted that while Edwards's charismatic style was in evidence, he had rushed through the speech, ending several minutes earlier than planned.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] In the days before the convention started, the other candidates withdrew, freed their delegates and officially endorsed Kerry.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] All the delegates voted to ratify this decision and vote for Kerry, except those of Kucinich, who attempted to vote for Kucinich anyway.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Many states refused to let them do so, and only permitted them to register abstentions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Prior to his speech, John Kerry's daughter spoke about her father.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] After the video's conclusion, former U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Senator Max Cleland delivered a speech proclaiming that the global conflict and active wars in Afghanistan and Iraq required a decorated military hero such as Kerry in the White House.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] This concluded with Kerry's entrance, where he made a military salute and announced, "I'm John Kerry, and I'm reporting for duty!" Kerry then accepted the nomination for president.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Democrats reacted positively to John Kerry's acceptance speech.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] With Democrats strongly opposed to the Bush administration, John Kerry spent most of his speech appealing to independent voters and to swing voters.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] On the day after Kerry's speech, George W.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Bush's reelection campaign launched a counterattack on the claims and promises made by Kerry and others at the convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] At a campaign stop in Springfield, Missouri, Bush told a crowd: "My opponent has good intentions, but intentions do not always translate to results", attacking Senator Kerry's record in the Senate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Ron Reagan, son of Republican president Ronald Reagan, also spoke at the convention, blaming Bush's hijacking of his father's legacy for his switch in support to the Democrats.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Polls conducted after Kerry's speech showed no significant increase of support (or "convention bounce") for the Democratic nominee's bid to unseat President Bush.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Democrats ascribed the disappointing numbers to an unusually polarized electorate that year with few undecided voters, though Bush did get a small bounce out of his convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] There were a number of demonstrations during the 2004 Democratic National Convention.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Protesters included members of the Bl(A)ck Tea Society, a group of self-described anarchists, who opposed the war in Iraq.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Approximately 400 members of the Bl(A)ck Tea Society marched through Boston's financial district and headed toward the FleetCenter, where they set fire to an effigy that showed George Bush on one side and John Kerry on the other.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] That evening a group of peace activists held a peaceful rally a few hundred feet from the FleetCenter.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Local Boston politicians were joined by presidential candidate Dennis Kucinich and long-time activist and California state senator Tom Hayden in a call to end the occupation of and to remove U.S. troops from Iraq and to bring in an international peacekeeping force.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] Also, Hayden and Kucinich called on anti-war Democrats to support John Kerry against George Bush in the general election.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The largest protest was held on the Sunday evening before the convention was set to start.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] An estimated 2,000 anti-war members marched at the same time as approximately 1,000 anti-abortion activists, and the two groups crossed paths en route to the convention center.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] The following day, this anti-abortion group had its permit revoked to protest outside of the Kerry family home.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2004-democratic-national-convention] They challenged the decision, but it was upheld by a federal judge, who sided with the Secret Service in determining that the protest would be too close to Kerry's home, potentially endangering the presidential candidate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Members of the Islamic militant group Ansar al-Sharia carried out a coordinated attack against two United States government facilities in Benghazi, Libya, on September 11, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At 9:40 p.m. local time, members of Ansar al-Sharia attacked the American diplomatic compound in Benghazi resulting in the deaths of both United States Ambassador to Libya J.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Foreign Service Information Management Officer Sean Smith.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At around 4:00 a.m. on September 12, the group launched a mortar attack against a CIA annex approximately one mile (1.6 km) away, killing CIA contractors Tyrone S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Woods and Glen Doherty and wounding ten others.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Initial analysis by the CIA, repeated by top government officials, indicated that the attack spontaneously arose from a protest.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Subsequent investigations showed that the attack was premeditated—although rioters and looters not originally part of the group may have joined in after the attacks began.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] There is no definitive evidence that al-Qaeda or any other international terrorist organization participated in the Benghazi attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The United States immediately increased security worldwide at diplomatic and military facilities and began investigating the Benghazi attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Libyan Government condemned the attacks and took steps to disband the militias.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] 30,000 Libyans marched through Benghazi condemning Ansar al-Sharia, which had been formed after the 2011 Libyan civil war which toppled Muammar Gaddafi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Despite numerous accusations against President Obama, Hillary Clinton, and Susan Rice, ten investigations did not find that they or any other high-ranking Obama administration officials had acted improperly.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Four career State Department officials were criticized for denying requests for additional security at the facility prior to the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Boswell, the Assistant Secretary of State for Diplomatic Security, resigned under pressure, while three others were suspended.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In her role as Secretary of State, Hillary Clinton subsequently took responsibility for the security lapses.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On August 6, 2013, it was reported that the United States had filed criminal charges against several individuals alleged to have been involved in the attacks, including militia leader Ahmed Abu Khattala.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Khattala has been described by both Libyan and United States officials as the Benghazi leader of Ansar al-Sharia.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The United States Department of State designated Ansar al-Sharia as a terrorist organization in January 2014.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Khattala was captured in Libya by United States Army Special Operations Forces, who were acting in coordination with the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), in June 2014.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Another suspect, Mustafa al-Imam, was captured in October 2017.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In February 2026, Zubayr al-Bakoush, who is believed to have played a central role in the attack, was captured and extradited to the United States.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The US had not had regular diplomatic presence in Libya since withdrawing its ambassador in 1972 and then closing its embassy after the 1979 U.S. embassy burning in Libya, but since the early 2000s had been starting to normalise relations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] During Congressional hearings, Ambassador J.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Christopher Stevens' top deputy in Libya, Gregory N.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Hicks, testified that Ambassador Stevens was in Benghazi in 2012 because "Secretary [of State Hillary] Clinton wanted the post made permanent", and it was understood that the secretary hoped to make an announcement to that effect during a visit to Tripoli later in the year.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In 2013, CNN reported that sources told it that around 35 US personnel were working in the diplomatic mission in Benghazi at the time of the attack, of whom around 21 were CIA officers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Within months of the start of the Libyan revolution in February 2011, the CIA had begun building a covert presence in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] During the war, elite counterterrorist operators from the United States Delta Force were deployed to Libya as analysts, instructing the rebels on specifics about weapons and tactics.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Christopher Stevens was named the first liaison with the Libyan opposition in March 2011.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Eastern Libya and Benghazi were key intelligence-gathering hubs for intelligence operatives.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Before the attack, the CIA was monitoring Ansar al-Sharia and suspected members of Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb, as well as attempting to define the leadership and loyalty of the various militias present and their interaction with the Salafi elements of Libyan society.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] By the time of the attack, dozens of CIA operatives were on the ground in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In addition, it has been reported that in the summer of 2012, American Joint Special Operations Command (JSOC) missions had begun to target Libyan militias linked to the Al-Qaeda network of Yasin al-Suri.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] By the time of the attack, a composite U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Special Operations team with two JSOC members was already in Libya working on their mission profile independently of the CIA and State Department operations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] There was some speculation that the diplomatic post in Benghazi was used by the CIA to smuggle weapons from Libya to anti-Assad rebels in Syria.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Investigative journalist Seymour Hersh cites an anonymous former senior Defense Department Intelligence Official, saying "The consulate's only mission was to provide cover for the moving of arms.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] It had no real political role." The attack allegedly brought an end to the purported United States involvement, but did not stop the smuggling according to Hersh's source.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In January 2014, the United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence cast doubt on this alleged United States involvement and reported that "All CIA activities in Benghazi were legal and authorized.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In April 2012, two former security guards for the consulate threw an IED over the consulate fence; the incident did not cause any casualties.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Just four days later, a similar bomb was thrown at a four-vehicle convoy carrying the United Nations Special Envoy to Libya, exploding twelve feet (3.7 m) from the United Nations envoy's vehicle without injuring anyone.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In May 2012, an Al-Qaida affiliate calling itself the "Brigades of the Imprisoned Sheikh Omar Abdul Rahman" claimed responsibility for an attack on the International Red Cross (ICRC) office in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On August 6, the ICRC suspended operations in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The head of the ICRC's delegation in Libya said the aid group was "appalled" by the attack and "extremely concerned" about escalating violence in Libya.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Brigades claimed that the attack was in response to the killing of Abu Yahya al Libi, a Libyan al-Qaeda leader who had just died in an American drone attack, and was also timed to coincide with the imminent arrival of a United States Diplomat.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] There were no injuries, but the group left behind leaflets promising more attacks against the United States.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] British Ambassador to Libya Dominic Asquith survived an assassination attempt in Benghazi on June 10, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Two British protection officers were injured in the attack when their convoy was hit by a rocket-propelled grenade 300 meters from their consulate office.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The British Foreign Office withdrew all consular staff from Benghazi in late June 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On June 18, 2012, the Tunisian Consulate in Benghazi was attacked by individuals affiliated with Ansar al-Sharia, allegedly because of "attacks by Tunisian artists against Islam".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On the day of the attack, two consulate security guards spotted a man in a Libyan police uniform taking pictures of the consulate with his cell phone from a nearby building that was under construction.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The security guards briefly detained the man before releasing him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He drove away in a police car and a complaint was made to the Libyan police station.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Sean Smith noticed this surveillance, and messaged a friend online around noon, "Assuming we don't die tonight.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] According to a local security official, he and a battalion commander had met with United States Diplomats three days before the attack and warned the Americans about deteriorating security in the area.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Ambassador Stevens' diary, which was later found at the compound, recorded his concern about the growing al-Qaeda presence in the area and his worry about being on an al-Qaeda hit list.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] United States Security Officer Eric Nordstrom twice requested additional security for the mission in Benghazi from the State Department.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] His requests were denied and according to Nordstrom, State Department Official Charlene Lamb wanted to keep the security presence in Benghazi "artificially low".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The desire of the State Department to maintain a low profile in Benghazi has been cited as the reason why the State Department circumvented their own Overseas Security Policy Board (OSPB) standards for diplomatic security.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In the aftermath, Clinton sought to take responsibility for the security lapses at Benghazi and expressed personal regret.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In her January 2013 testimony before Congress, Secretary Clinton claimed security decisions at the Benghazi compound had been made by others, stating, "The specific security requests pertaining to Benghazi ... were handled by the security professionals in the [State] Department.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Benghazi attack was conducted by separate military factions on two separate United States compounds.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The first assault occurred at the main diplomatic compound, approximately 300 yards (270 m) long and 100 yards (91 m) wide, at about 9:40 p.m. local time (3:40 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A mortar fire attack on a CIA annex 1.2 miles (1.9 km) away began at about 4:00 a.m. the following morning and lasted for 11 minutes.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A Libyan guard who was wounded in the attack later said "there wasn't a single ant outside [before the attack]." According to Media Matters For America, the attackers stated they were acting in response to *Innocence of Muslims*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] No more than seven Americans were in the compound, including Ambassador Stevens.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Stevens was visiting Benghazi at the time to review plans to establish a new cultural center and modernize a hospital.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The ambassador also "needed to [prepare a] report ... on the physical and the political and security environment in Benghazi to support an action memo to convert Benghazi from a temporary facility to a permanent facility".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Surplus funds originally dedicated for use in Iran for fiscal year 2012 were to be redirected and obligated for use in Benghazi: an action that had to be completed before the end of the fiscal year—September 30, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Stevens had his last meeting of the day with a Turkish diplomat (Consul General Ali Sait Akın), and escorted the Turkish diplomat to the main gate at about 8:30 p.m. local time.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The street outside the compound was calm, and the State Department reported no unusual activity during the day outside.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Stevens retired to his room at about 9:00 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] CAT, large numbers of armed men approached the compound from multiple directions.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] They then threw grenades over the wall and entered the compound with automatic weapons fire, RPGs, and heavier weapons.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A Diplomatic Security Service (DSS) agent viewed on the consulate's security cameras "a large number of men, armed men, flowing into the compound".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He hit the alarm and started shouting, "Attack!
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Phone calls were made to the embassy in Tripoli, the Diplomatic Security Command Center in Washington, the February 17th Martyrs Brigade and a U.S. quick reaction force located at the annex compound a little more than a mile (1.6 km) away.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Diplomatic Security Service Special Agent Scott Wickland secured Stevens and Sean Smith, an information management officer, in the main building's safe haven.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The rest of the agents left to retrieve their weapons and tried to return to the main building.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The attackers entered the main building and attempted to enter the safe haven.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] They then spread diesel fuel in the room and set fires.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Stevens, Smith, and Wickland moved to the nearby bathroom, but then decided to leave the safe haven after being overcome by smoke.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Wickland exited through the window, but Stevens and Smith did not follow him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Wickland (who was severely wounded by gunfire) returned several times but could not find them in the smoke; he went up to the roof and radioed other agents.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Three agents returned to the main building in an armored vehicle, searched the building and found Smith's body, but not Stevens.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] According to the Annex Security Team, they had become aware of the consulate attack after 9:30 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] CAT, and were ready to respond; however, they were delayed by "the top CIA officer in Benghazi".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Regional Security Office sounded the alarm and called to the Benghazi CIA annex and the embassy in Tripoli.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] After some discussion, the CIA's Global Response Staff (GRS) at the CIA annex, which included Tyrone S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] By 10:05 p.m., the team was briefed and loaded into their armored Toyota Land Cruisers.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] By this time, communicators at the CIA annex were notifying the chain of command about current developments, and a small CIA and JSOC element in Tripoli that included Glen Doherty was attempting to find a way to Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The GRS team from the CIA annex arrived at the consulate and attempted to secure the perimeter and locate the ambassador and Sean Smith.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Diplomatic security agent David Ubben located Smith, who was unconscious and later declared dead, but the team was unable to find Stevens in the smoke-filled building.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The team then decided to return to the annex with the survivors and Smith's body.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] While en route back to the annex, the group's armored vehicle was hit by AK-47 rifle fire and hand grenades.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The vehicle was able to make it to its destination with two flat tires, and the gates to the annex were closed behind them at 11:50 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At the time, AFRICOM, which is responsible for operations in Africa, was the only combatant command which did not have its own CIF team thus having to request EUCOM's assistance.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] These teams were sent to Naval Air Station Sigonella in Sicily, Italy as a staging point on the night of the attack but did not deploy to Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] United States officials stated the teams arrived at Sigonella after the attack was over.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Diplomatic Security Service agents/Regional Security Officers informed their headquarters in Washington about the attack just as it was beginning at about 9:40 p.m. local time (3:40 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At the time, they were informed that the attack was a "terrorist attack".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] However, through September 14, CIA analysts made a contradictory assessment, stating "We believe based on currently available information that the attacks in Benghazi were spontaneously inspired by the protests at the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Embassy in Cairo and evolved into a direct assault against the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The crowd almost certainly was a mix of individuals from across many sectors of Libyan society.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] ET, Pentagon officials had informed Defense Secretary Leon Panetta about the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Pentagon ordered an unmanned aerial vehicle that was in the air conducting surveillance on militant camps to fly over Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The drone arrived at 11:10 p.m. local time (5:10 p.m.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] ET) and began providing a video feed to Washington.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] ET, Secretary of State Hillary Clinton telephoned CIA Director David Petraeus to coordinate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The CIA, which made up most of the U.S. government's presence in Benghazi, had a ten-member security team at its annex and the State Department believed that this team would assist the consulate in the event of an attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Just after midnight, the CIA annex came under machine gun, rocket and mortar fire.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The CIA defenders held off the attack until the morning.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] That same morning, Libyan government forces met up with a group of Americans, reinforcements from Tripoli including Glen Doherty, that had arrived at the Benghazi airport.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The team, which included two active-duty JSOC operators and five CIA personnel, had commandeered a small jet in Tripoli by paying the pilots $30,000 and forcing them to fly to Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] After being held up at the airport for a few hours, the Libyan forces and newly arrived Americans went to the CIA annex at about 5:00 a.m. to assist in transporting approximately 32 Americans at the annex back to the airport for evacuation.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Minutes after they drove through the gates, the annex came under heavy fire.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] With a lull in the fighting, Doherty began searching for his friend, Tyrone S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Woods, and he was told he was on the roof.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He found Woods on the roof with two other agents.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A mortar round then hit Woods' position, fatally wounding him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] As Doherty attempted to reposition and take cover, a second round fell on him, killing him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] 31-year-old Diplomatic Security Service Special Agent David Ubben and 46-year-old CIA contractor Mark Geist suffered shrapnel injuries and several broken bones in the mortar attacks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Immediately, several agents ran onto the roof to assess damage and help the wounded.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At the same time, a JSOC operator was using a hand-held device displaying images from a Predator drone above, which had been sent by the DOD's US Africa Command after request.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The defenders agreed to evacuate to the airport and were attacked with small arms fire along the route.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The evacuation of about 30 Americans included six State Department personnel and Smith's body—they were unable to locate Ambassador Stevens at the time.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Ambassador Stevens' body was found by a group of Libyans who had accessed the room through a window.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] They were unaware of his identity, and Abdel-Qader Fadl, a freelance photographer who was with them, told the Associated Press that Stevens was unconscious and "maybe moved his head, but only once".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Ahmed Shams, a 22-year-old arts student, told the Associated Press that they were happy when they found Stevens alive and tried to rescue him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A freelance videographer, Fahd al-Bakoush, later published a video showing Libyans trying to extract the ambassador from a smoke-filled room, where he was found unconscious.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] According to al-Bakoush, the Libyans saw he was alive and breathing, his eyelids flickering.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Though they took him to be a foreigner, no one recognized him as Stevens.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] At around 1:00 a.m., Stevens was taken to the Benghazi Medical Center, a hospital controlled by the Ansar Al-Sharia militia, in a private car as there was no ambulance to carry him.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] There he was administered CPR for 90 minutes by Dr.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Zeid, Stevens died from asphyxiation caused by smoke inhalation, and had no other apparent injuries.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The doctor said he believed that officers from the Libyan Interior Ministry transported the body to the airport.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] State Department officials said they do not know who took Stevens to the hospital or transported the body to the airport and into U.S. custody.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The bodies were taken to Benina International Airport and flown to the capital, Tripoli, and then to Ramstein Air Base in Germany aboard a C-17 military transport aircraft.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] From Germany, the four bodies arrived at Andrews Air Force Base near Washington, D.C., where President Barack Obama and members of his cabinet held a ceremony in honor of those killed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] After the attack, all diplomatic staff were moved to the capital, Tripoli, with nonessential personnel to be flown out of Libya.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Sensitive documents remained missing, including documents listing the names of Libyans working with the Americans, and documents relating to oil contracts.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Four Americans died in the attack: Ambassador J.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Christopher Stevens, Information Officer Sean Smith, and two CIA operatives, Glen Doherty and Tyrone S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Stevens was the first United States ambassador killed in an attack since Adolph Dubs was killed in Kabul, Afghanistan, in 1979.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] It is uncertain how much prior knowledge of the attack al-Zawahiri had, though he praised the attackers on October 12, 2012, in another video.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On September 14, 2012, al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula released a statement arguing the attack was revenge for the death of al-Libi, though they did not claim official responsibility for the Benghazi attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] It was later reported that 3 operatives from the group did take part in the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Furthermore, an intercepted phone call from the Benghazi area immediately after the attack reportedly linked senior Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb commander Mokhtar Belmokhtar to the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] David Kirkpatrick of *The New York Times* reported that 20-year-old neighbor Mohamed Bishari witnessed the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] According to Bishari, it was launched without warning or protest and was led by the Islamist militia Ansar al-Sharia (different from the group called Ansar al-Sharia based in Yemen designated by the U.N. and the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Department of State as a terrorist organization).
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Kirkpatrick reported that Ansar al-Sharia said they were launching the assault in retaliation for the release of the anti-Islamic video, *Innocence of Muslims*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] It was further reported that Ahmed Abu Khattala was called a ringleader of the attack by both witnesses and authorities, though he insisted he did not play a part in the aggression at the American compound.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Witnesses, Benghazi residents, and Western news reports have described him as a leader of Ansar al-Sharia, though he stated he was close to the group but not an official part of it.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He further stated he was the commander of an Islamist brigade, Abu Obaida ibn al-Jarrah, some of whose members had joined Ansar al-Sharia.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The Brigades of the Imprisoned Sheikh Omar Abdul Rahman, a pro-al-Qaeda militia calling for the release of The Blind Sheikh, was implicated in the attack by Noman Benotman of the Quilliam Foundation.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] CNN, the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, *Commentary Magazine* and *The Daily Telegraph* have listed this group as a chief suspect.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] *USA Today* reported that protests in Cairo that preceded the attack on Benghazi were intended to protest the imprisonment of Sheik Omar Abdul Rahman and announced as early as August 30.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Egyptian President Mohammed Morsi had called for the release of the Blind Sheikh in his inaugural address.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] During the hours before the attack, Egyptian satellite television networks popular in Benghazi had been covering the outrage over the video.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In a phone call with the Egyptian prime minister Kandil the day after the attack, then-Secretary of State Hillary Clinton said "we know the attack in Libya had nothing to do with the film.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] However, this assessment contradicted the assessment of CIA analysts, which through September 16 maintained that "the demonstrations in Benghazi were spontaneously inspired by the protests at the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Embassy in Cairo," at which violent protesters had scaled the embassy walls.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In October 2012, a Tunisian, Ali Harzi, who a U.S. intelligence official stated had links to Ansar al-Sharia and al-Qaeda in the Maghreb, was arrested in Turkey and repatriated to Tunisia on terrorism charges and possible links to the attack on the U.S. consulate in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Ali Harzi was released by Tunisian authorities on January 8, 2013, because of a lack of evidence.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Also in October, a Libyan suspect, Karim el-Azizi, who had recently returned to Egypt from Libya and was storing weapons in his hideout, detonated a bomb and was found dead in his apartment after clashes with security forces.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He has been linked to an Egyptian terrorist group led by Muhammad Jamal Abu Ahmad, who is suspected of training some of the terrorists responsible for the Benghazi attack in camps in the Libyan desert.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Jamal Abu Ahmad, a former member of Egyptian Islamic Jihad, was released from Egyptian prison after the fall of the Mubarak regime, after which he began assembling a terrorist network.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He received financing from the Yemen-based Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula, petitioned Al-Qaeda leader Ayman al-Zawahiri to establish a new Al-Qaeda affiliate he called al-Qaeda in Egypt, and was subsequently detained by Egyptian authorities in December 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On October 7, 2013, the Muhammad Jamal network (MJN) and Muhammad Jamal were designated as Specially Designated Global Terrorists by the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Department of State, which noted in its designation that "Jamal has developed connections with al-Qa'ida in the Islamic Maghreb (AQIM), AQ senior leadership, and al-Qa'ida in the Arabian Peninsula (AQAP) leadership including Nasir 'Abd-al-Karim 'Abdullah al-Wahishi and Qasim Yahya Mahdi al-Rimi".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] A few days later, on October 21, 2013, the United Nations Security Council designated the Muhammad Jamal network "as being associated with Al-Qaida".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] The United Nations Security Council also noted, "Some of the attackers of the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In March 2013, Faraj al-Shibli was detained by Libyan authorities and questioned by the FBI because of his suspected involvement in the Benghazi attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Al-Shibli was detained after he returned from a trip to Pakistan, though his exact role in the attack is unclear.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He was a member of the Libyan Islamic Fighting Group, which tried to overthrow the Gadhafi regime in the mid-1990s.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Investigators have learned he has had contact with both the Yemen-based Al-Qaeda in the Arabian Peninsula and Al-Qaeda members in Pakistan.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] He was released by Libyan authorities on June 12, 2013, based on claims there was a lack of evidence to hold him in custody.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] In July 2014 he was found dead in Libya.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] On February 6, 2026, the United States announced that it had captured a key participant in the attack named Zubayr Al-Bakoush.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Following his arrest, Al-Bakoush was then transferred from Misrata, Libya and landed at Manassas Regional Airport in Virginia at 3 am.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p01] Al-Bakoush is believed to have "conducted surveillance activity" after entering the compound when the fires were set and tried to gain access to the vehicles which were located on the grounds of the compound.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Mohamed Yousef el-Magariaf, the President of the General National Congress of Libya, said: "We apologize to the U.S., to the American people and to the government and also to the rest of the world for what happened yesterday.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] There were demonstrations in Benghazi and Tripoli on September 12, condemning the violence and holding signs such as "Chris Stevens was a friend to all Libyans", "Benghazi is against terrorism", and other signs apologizing to Americans for the actions in their name and in the name of Muslims.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On the same day, Libya's Deputy Ambassador to the United Kingdom Ahmad Jibril told the BBC that Ansar Al-Sharia was behind the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] State Department reception in Washington D.C., the Libyan ambassador to the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Ali Aujali apologized to Secretary of State Clinton for "this terrorist attack which took place against the American consulate in Libya".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The ambassador further praised Stevens as a "dear friend" and a "real hero".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] He also urged the United States to continue supporting Libya as it went "through a very difficult time" and that the young Libyan government needed help so that it could "maintain ... security and stability in our country".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In the days after the attack, *The New York Times* stated that young Libyans had flooded Twitter with pro-American messages after the attacks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] *Think Progress* stated that Libyans are typically more positively inclined towards the United States than their neighbors.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 21, about 30,000 Libyans marched through Benghazi calling for support of the rule of law and for an end to the armed militias that had formed during the Libyan Civil War to oppose Colonel Gaddafi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] After that war, the militias failed to disband, and continually menaced the Libyan government and populace.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Carrying signs with slogans such as "We Want Justice For Chris" and "Libya Lost a Friend", the protestors stormed several militia headquarters, including that of Ansar al-Sharia, an Islamist militia who some allege played a role in the attack on U.S. diplomatic personnel on September 11.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] At least 10 people were killed and dozens more wounded as militiamen fired on demonstrators at the headquarters of Sahaty Brigade, a pro-government militia "operating under the authority of the ministry of defence".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] By early next morning, the protestors had forced militia members to flee and seized control of a number of compounds, releasing four prisoners found inside.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Protesters burnt a car and a building of at least one facility, and looted weapons.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The militia compounds and many weapons were handed over to Libya's national army in what "appeared to be part of a coordinated sweep of militia bases by police, government troops and activists" following the earlier demonstrations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Some militia members accused the protestors of being Gaddafi loyalists, looking to disarm the militias in the wake of the revolution.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 23, taking advantage of the growing momentum and rising anger against the militias evinced in the earlier anti-militia demonstrations, the Libyan president declared that all unauthorized militias had 48 hours to either disband or come under government control.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The government also mandated that bearing arms in public was now illegal, as were armed checkpoints.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Handling the militias had been difficult as the government had been forced to rely on some of them for protection and security.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] According to a Libyan interviewed in Tripoli, the government gained the ability to push back against the militias because of a "mandate of the people".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 24, the government commenced with a raid on a former military base held by a rogue infantry militia.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Across the country, militias began surrendering to the government.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The government formed a "National Mobile Force" for the purpose of evicting illegal militias.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Hours before the announcement, in Derna, the two main militias (one of them Ansar al-Sharia) active in the city both withdrew, leaving both their five military bases behind.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Hundreds of Libyans, mainly former rebel fighters, gathered in the city centers of Tripoli and Benghazi to hand over their weapons to the government on September 29.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The campaign has been less successful in other areas, such as the remote Nafusa Mountains, inhabited by the Nafusi-speaking Berber minority, where the Emirati news agency The National reported on September 23 that arms were being hoarded.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The National also reported arms being hoarded in Misrata, despite simultaneous reporting by other outlets that militias were surrendering in Misrata.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] President Barack Obama condemned "this outrageous attack" on U.S. diplomatic facilities and stated that "since our founding, the United States has been a nation that respects all faiths.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] After the attack, Obama ordered that security be increased at all such facilities worldwide.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] A 50-member Marine FAST team was sent to Libya to "bolster security".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] It was announced that the FBI would investigate the possibility of the attack being planned.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] U.S. officials said surveillance over Libya would increase, including the use of unmanned drones, to "hunt for the attackers".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Secretary of State Clinton also made a statement on September 12, describing the perpetrators as "heavily armed militants" and "a small and savage group—not the people or government of Libya".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The State Department had previously identified embassy and personnel security as a major challenge in its budget and priorities report.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 12, it was reported that the United States Navy dispatched two *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers, USS *McFaul* and USS *Laboon*, to the Libyan coast.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The destroyers are equipped with Tomahawk cruise missiles.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] American UAVs were also sent to fly over Libya to search for the perpetrators of the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 14, the remains of the slain Americans were returned to the U.S.; President Obama and Secretary of State Hillary Clinton attended the ceremony.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Susan Rice appeared on five major interview shows to discuss the attacks.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Since Rice's five television appearances, there have been persistent accusations that she had intentionally and repeatedly lied.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] However, none of the ten Benghazi investigations determined she had.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] For example, the Republican-controlled House Intelligence Committee "did not conclude that Rice or any other government official acted in bad faith or intentionally misled the American people," according to the Associated Press.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 20, White House Press Secretary Jay Carney answered a question about an open hearing with the National Counterterrorism Center Director, Matthew G.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Olsen, which referenced which extremist groups might have been involved.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Carney said, "It is, I think, self-evident that what happened in Benghazi was a terrorist attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Our embassy was attacked violently, and the result was four deaths of American officials.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Also on September 20, Secretary of State Hillary Clinton gave a classified briefing to U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Senators, which several Republican attendees criticized.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] According to the article, senators were angered at the Obama administration's rebuff of their attempts to learn details of the Benghazi attack, only to see that information published the next day in *The New York Times* and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 24, advertisements condemning an anti-Islam video appeared on Pakistani television.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The television ads in Pakistan (marked with the U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Embassy seal) feature clips of President Obama and Secretary of State Clinton during press appearances in Washington in which they condemned the video.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 25, in an address before the United Nations General Assembly President Obama stated, "The attacks on our civilians in Benghazi were attacks on America ...
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] And there should be no doubt that we will be relentless in tracking down the killers and bringing them to justice." He referred to *Innocence of Muslims* as "a crude and disgusting video [that] sparked outrage throughout the Muslim world".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 26, Clinton acknowledged a possible link between Al-Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Benghazi attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Also on September 28, it was reported that Nakoula Basseley Nakoula, the producer of the *Innocence of Muslims* video, had been arrested in California and was being held without bail for alleged probation violations stemming from a 2010 bank fraud conviction.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On October 4, 22 days after the attack, FBI investigators were finally allowed access to the scene of the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The crime scene was not secured during that time; neither American nor Libyan investigators were able to secure the scene.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The hearing testimony revealed that "Hicks argued that Rice's comments so insulted the Libyan president—since they contradicted his Sept.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] 16 claims that the attack was premeditated—that it slowed the FBI's investigation.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] 'President Magariaf was insulted in front of his own people, in front of the world.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] To assist the Libyan government in disbanding extremist groups, the Obama administration allocated $8 million to begin building an elite Libyan commando force over the next year.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] "That this was an act of terror, and I also said that we're going to hunt down those who committed this crime." When Romney challenged Obama, asking "You said in the Rose Garden the day after the attack, it was an act of terror.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On October 19, 2012, House Oversight Committee Chairman Darrell Issa (R-CA) came under fire from intelligence officials in the Obama administration when he posted, on a public website, 166 pages of sensitive but unclassified State Department communications related to Libya.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] According to officials, the release of the unredacted documents compromised the identities of several Libyans working with the U.S. government and placed their lives in danger.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On CBS's *Face the Nation* on October 28, Senator John McCain (R-AZ) stated that "this is either a massive cover-up or incompetence" and suggested that it was a scandal worse than Watergate.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] McCain stated, "we know that there were tapes, recordings inside the consulate during this fight ...
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] And what did he do about it?" CBS News reported earlier on October 24 that the video of the assault was not recovered until 20 days after the attack, from the more than 10 security cameras at the compound.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In a radio interview October 29, 2012, Senator John McCain said that the surveillance tapes had been classified top secret.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Secretary Clinton was scheduled to testify before Congress on December 20 about the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On December 15, it was reported that she had become dehydrated from the flu, fainted, and sustained a concussion.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Consequently, her testimony was postponed.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Allen West to claim that the illness was a ruse intended to avoid testifying.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Former UN Ambassador John Bolton called the concussion a "diplomatic illness".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On January 23, 2013, during testimony at a Senate hearing on Benghazi, Clinton engaged in a heated exchange with Senator Ron Johnson.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Hunter introduced legislation into the 113th Congress to authorize awarding of Congressional Gold Medals to Doherty and Woods for their actions that led to their deaths.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In April 2013, the Pentagon announced the activation of a USMC quick response force for North Africa that would use the range and speed of the Bell Boeing V-22 Osprey to be able to respond to similar events in the future.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Spain authorized the basing of the quick response force at Morón Air Base near Seville, for a temporary one-year term.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Ed Royce (R, CA-39) introduced the Department of State Operations and Embassy Security Authorization Act, Fiscal Year 2014 (H.R.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] contracting at high risk, high threat posts; to authorize security improvements at soft targets; and to provide for security enhancements in line with Accountability Review Board recommendations.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Critics including Republican Party members accused the Obama White House and State Department of overemphasizing or fabricating the role of Islamic anger over the anti-Islamic movie *Innocence of Muslims* and alleged that the administration was reluctant to label the attack as "terrorist".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] It was clearly designed to be an attack." According to critics, the consulate site should have been secured better both before and after the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] GOP legislators also took issue with delays in the investigation, which CNN attributed to "bureaucratic infighting" between the FBI, Justice, and State.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On September 26, Senator Johnny Isakson (R-Georgia) said he "cannot believe that the FBI is not on the ground yet".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Testimony from top U.S. commanders after the attack revealed that the military was unprepared for conflict across Africa and the Middle East.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] No attack aircraft had been placed on high alert on September 11, the anniversary of the September 11 attacks in 2001, and the closest fighter planes to trouble spots in North Africa were based in Aviano, Italy.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The fighter planes based in Aviano were unarmed and no aerial refueling planes were within a 10-hour flight to the base.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In addition, no AC-130 gunships were within a 10-hour flight of Libya, and their crews did not reach a staging base in Italy until 19 hours after the attack began.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] With the attack and subsequent criticism occurring in the last two months of the 2012 U.S. presidential election, Democrats and liberal media figures accused Republicans of politicizing the attacks in an unprecedented manner.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Romney was accused by the Obama campaign of trying to exploit the attacks for political gain, leading the father of Ambassador Stevens to call for both campaigns to avoid making it a campaign issue.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Robert Gates, former CIA director and Defense Secretary under Republican Presidents and then President Obama, said that some critics of the government's response have a "cartoonish" view of military capabilities.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] He stated that he would have responded with equal caution given the risks and the lack of intelligence on the ground, and that American forces require planning and preparation, which the circumstances did not allow for.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] President Obama called the criticism a "sideshow" and later accused Congress of "taking its eye off the ball" on the subject of the economy and focusing on "phony scandals".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] White House Spokesman Jay Carney later specified that the criticism of the administration's handling of the Benghazi attacks was one of those "phony scandals".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] For actions in Benghazi during the attack, Marine Gunnery Sergeant Tate Jolly was awarded the Navy Cross, and Army Master Sergeant David R.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Halbruner was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In January 2020 Mustafa al-Imam, a Libyan man accused of scouting for the Benghazi attackers, was sentenced to over 19 years in prison by a federal Washington judge.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The Center for Media and Public Affairs at George Mason University described the conclusions of an unpublished study on November 2, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Obama administration officials, most notably Susan Rice, were provided this early assessment and repeated it to media outlets, only to be later contradicted as further intelligence assessments were made.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] None of the ten investigations into Benghazi found that any senior Obama administration officials had acted improperly.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] However, the day after the Benghazi attack, Ansar al-Sharia issued a statement saying that the attack was in part "a spontaneous popular uprising in response to what happened by the West," which was an apparent reference to the *Innocence of Muslims* video.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Conservative pundit Jonah Goldberg of the *National Review* stated that on NBC's *Meet the Press*, host David Gregory changed the subject when a guest raised the subject of the Benghazi attack, saying, "Let's get to Libya a little bit later", but never returned to the subject.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On November 26, 2012, journalist Tom Ricks went on Fox News' *Happening Now* with Jon Scott to discuss the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] While being interviewed on Fox News by Jon Scott, Ricks accused Fox News of being "extremely political" in its coverage of the attack and said that "Fox was operating as a wing of the Republican Party." Ricks accused the network of covering the story more than it needed to be.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The interview was cut short and Ricks and the interview was not mentioned or covered by Fox News again.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Fox News was subsequently criticized for cutting the interview short.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] In an interview with the Associated Press, Fox News' White House correspondent Ed Henry suggested that he thought Benghazi was being covered too much by the network.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] There were ten investigations into the Benghazi matter: one by the FBI; one by an independent board commissioned by the State Department; two by Democrat-controlled Senate Committees; and six by Republican-controlled House Committees.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] After the first five Republican investigations found no evidence of wrongdoing by senior Obama administration officials, Republicans in 2014 opened a sixth investigation, the House Select Committee on Benghazi, chaired by Trey Gowdy.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] This investigation also failed to find any evidence of wrongdoing by senior Obama administration officials.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] But we put together a Benghazi special committee, a select committee.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Her numbers are dropping." The United States Marines responsible for State Department security, the security lapse was called "the result of opportunism" in 2012 by Carney.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Shortly after the Benghazi attack, Secretary of State Clinton commissioned an independent Accountability Review Board to investigate, chaired by retired ambassador Thomas R.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Pickering with vice-chair retired Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff Michael Mullen.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The Board released their final report on December 19, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] It made 29 recommendations to the State Department on how to improve its operations, which Clinton pledged to implement.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] As part of this investigation, four career State Department officials were criticized for denying requests for additional security at the facility prior to the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] None of the other Benghazi investigations identified wrongdoing by any individuals.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The House Select Committee on Benghazi's final report was released on June 28, 2016, and the committee closed down five months later.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] It criticized the actions and speed of response of the State Department, and the Defense Department, leading up to and during the attacks in Benghazi.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] No further public investigations have been conducted since.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Freedom of Information Act requests have been made since the attack.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] The conservative activist group Judicial Watch filed a FOIA request to the Department of State on December 19, 2012.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] An acknowledgement of the request was received by Judicial Watch on January 4, 2013.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] When the State Department failed to respond to the request by February 4, 2013, Judicial Watch filed a lawsuit, which resulted in seven photographs being delivered on June 6, 2013.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Three of the photographs show Arabic-language spray paint graffiti.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On May 30, 2013, it was reported that the Republican National Committee filed a FOIA for "any and all emails or other documents containing the terms 'Libya' and/or 'Benghazi' dated between September 11, 2012 and November 7, 2012 directed from or to U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Department of State employees originating from, or addressed to, persons whose email addresses end in either 'barackobama.com' or 'dnc.org'".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] On April 18, 2014, Judicial Watch released more than 100 pages of documents obtained through a FOIA lawsuit.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] One email, dated September 14, 2012, with a subject line "RE PREP CALL with Susan: Saturday at 4:00 pm ET", was from deputy national security advisor for strategic communications Rhodes stated: "Goals: ...
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] According to *The Wall Street Journal*, the e-mail was written to prepare U.S.
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] Susan Rice for her appearances on Sunday news shows two days later, and it "sets out the Administration's view of the cause of the Benghazi attacks".
[src:2012-benghazi-attack/2012-benghazi-attack-p02] John Dickerson of *Slate* says the e-mail refers to the worldwide protests against *Innocence of Muslims* and not the Benghazi attack.
